 Welt und Mensch durch den mittelalterlichen Menschen. Ziel des interdisziplinär konzipierten Bandes ist es zu zeigen, wie das Tier in maßgeblichen mittelalterlichen Diskursen (Religion und Wissenschaft, Jagdalltag und Wappenwesen, Literatur und Kunst) zum Medium der Erkenntnis und Vergegenwärtigung, der Strukturierung und Ordnung sowie der Deutung und Bewältigung von Welt wird.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aAnimals (Philosophy)xHistory. 0aAnimals, MythicalxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aHuman-animal relationshipsxHistory. 0aMythologyxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aFabeltier. 4aMittelalter. 4aTier ‹Motiv›. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnimals.  aMiddle Ages.  aMythical creatures.1 aAnzulewicz, Henryk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBosold-DasGupta, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranz, Leonie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartmann, Heiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonegger, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehmann, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehnardt, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aObermaier, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aObermaier, Sabine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPelizaeus, Anette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrietzel, Kathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRapp, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmets, An, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWille, Clara, econtributor.4